metadata.name: Traveler #90
metadata.description:
Retro sci-fi style landscape sketch drawn by code.

Features:
- Terrain: Cliff, Cavern, Sky, Megalopolis, Desert, Sea, Space, Volcano
- Orientation: Landscape, Portlait
- Palette: White, Cream, Tan, Pink, Green, Yellow, Orange
- Background: Light, Dark

Live view options:

Depending on the device you run it on, it may take some time for the drawing to complete.
Made with p5js.

June 2022
ykxotkx

metadata.name: Strata #28
metadata.description:
A generative series inspired by the work of Vera Molnár, Strata explores the diversity that can come from one shape - the simple rectangle.

With 16 properties and ~600 palettes, I hope that each mint offers something unique and special.

Exploration is fully open and will be left open post-mint :)

metadata.name: impossible cathedrals #319
metadata.description:
When the Impressionists first exhibited their work, they derided as lunatics by the art establishment. The vitriol then -- "wallpaper in its embryonic state is more finished than that seascape" (referring to Impression: sunrise by Monet) -- reminds me of criticism that generative art, and the NFT world more generally, are subject to now. "Impossible cathedrals" is a tribute to rebels who dare to see the world differently. 

Since generative art is often criticized as cold and austere, I took this as a challenge to reproduce the spirit of impressionism. Impossible cathedrals -- interwoven arches that cannot exist in reality -- hint at some of the favorite subjects of the impressionists.

The title alludes to Italo Calvino's novel Invisible Cities, a rebel in another context. Other artists who I had in mind during creation: the Japanese woodblock printing artists Kawase Hasui and Hiroshi Yoshida; American painter JAM Whistler.

Impossible cathedrals was written in p5.js using elements of code by eeedg (thanks)

metadata.name: Action; System #8
metadata.description:
Action; system is an experimental study inspired by the work of François Morellet. Morellet was one of the founders of the Groupe de Recherche d'Art Visuel (GRAV), founded in the 60s. His work was often informed by systems, a set of rules that determine the artwork, reducing the artist's subjectivity to a minimum.

This work explores what happens when we let go of the strict rule set. Do we ever fully let go?

-----------------
This work was released for the 2023 fundraising exhibition Cure3, and all of the proceeds and 1% of royalties will go to Parkinson's research funds. You can find more information at https://cure3.co.uk/.

-----------------
Controls
- R: new randomized output (the chances of recovering one of these outputs are very slim, that's what the next control is for)
- E: high-res output
- Double click: fullscreen

While you see the eye of Horus, your artwork is loading.

------------------
Made with p5.js & glsl
License: CC BY-NC-ND 4.0

metadata.name: Make-believe #4
metadata.description:
#genuary32nd – Let's meet on this make-believe date, in this make-believe place.
I’m having déjà vu, or is it a memory?

This artwork is originally created for the genuary2023 prompt "Art Deco", using the same core algorithm as Memory Module. Made with fractal math and p5js.

Keyboard controls:
[s] Save the current view in live mode.
[1] to [8] Change resolution, 1.5K to 12K.
[g] Toggle texture.

URL params:
&aspect=[aspect ratio, eg 2]
&res=[resolution multiplier, 0.5-8]

Created by Elsif, 2023.02

metadata.name: On Time #208
metadata.description:
[ CLICK TO START THE SOUND ]

Often, I find myself feeling like I'm running behind, or that time is slipping away too quickly. I struggle to be present in the moment because of anxieties related to the past or the future.

"On Time" explores the elusive nature of time and my relationship with it. Through this project, I aimed to create an experience that captures the way that we each experience time in our own way. Seeing that time is not linear but instead, it ebbs and flows in different ways.

At the heart of the experience is a visual reminder to stay in the moment and embrace it. The project consists of 256 unique visuals, each one representing a fleeting moment that has been captured in digital form. These moments are presented in a way that allows you to observe them, appreciate them, and stay present in them. "On Time" is an invitation to pause, take a deep breath, and remind ourselves that we are always where we need to be.

Controls
[ f ] - fullscreen
[ s ] - save the current frame as an image

Created with Three.js
Copyright (c) Dec. 2022 - Feb. 2023 Shaderism

metadata.name: Omega Point #17
metadata.description:
In the collapsing universe approaching singularity, the last remaining cybernetic organisms encounter the state of infinite knowledge, information, and computational resources.
Although the living creatures in the Omega Point are destined for imminent destruction, they experience infinite life.

----

Live mode controls:
'r' - change resolution
's' - save PNG
'space' - improve image quality
'f' - increase rendering speed

The image quality gradually improves over time, up to a certain level. To reach the maximum quality, press 'space'.
The rendering speed is reduced by default - press 'f' for the maximum speed.

Rendering may be GPU intensive.
Requires WebGL2.

metadata.name: Aurora At Mount St. Matrice #2
metadata.description:
At the gateway of waking and sleep, warmed by a molten heart; into the arms of night - be bathed by her falling hair.

Process: Forged in Hydra.

🌐 A note on rarity and variety: 

Although there are many variations possible within this piece, they are on the subtler side.

As this is a highly temporal piece, these variations ask you to dive into the experience of the piece in order to fully appreciate them. Please proceed bearing this in mind.

Experiment with the aspect ratio of this piece using the ‘open live’ function below the viewport - it can be enjoyed elastically [as with my previous works here]. A larger frame provides for a deeper experience.

As with a handful of my works, an instance of .blend() is used in this piece, and does cause some slight thinning and dimming to the preview capture. Once more, this still preview is to be considered a skeletal scan of a moment within this piece.

metadata.name: Tone Row #46
metadata.description:
Tone Row

Audiovisual composition. Click anywhere to start/stop the sound.

“Tone Row” is a text-score from the book “ImageAudio: A Post-Digital Event Score Anthology” by Zach Dawson (22.02.24). This NFT is my realisation of ‘Tone Row’, the last text score from the book. With each iteration, the algorithm composes a new, unique piece of music along with an audio-reactive animation, executing one possible take on the text score.

Tone Row (text-score by Zach Dawson):

“Source 12 separate micro sound samples.
Pitch shift each sample to 12 separate pitches.
Compose music with the tone row of samples.”

ImageAudio book: https://archive.org/details/imageaudio-book/mode/2up

—

Credits:
Commissioned by Zach Dawson, author of the ImageAudio project.
Music, visuals, and composition coded by Adam Łukawski (sunsetsobserver).
Background images come from the ImageAudio book, initiated by Zach Dawson and designed by Richard Stenton.

Handjet font designed by Rosetta, David Březina and served under the Open Font License.

Libraries used:
Tone.js
Hydra Video Synth
FxHash

Please note that on iOS the sound playback might not work if the device is in mute mode.

—

Find more of my projects at:
www.adamlukawski.com

metadata.name: Annum #8521
metadata.description:
This project is being released in celebration of the 1 year aniversary of Achromat, my first release on fxhash. In addition to being inspired by Achromat, aspects of other previous projects have been incorporated. My deepest gratitude to all who have collected my work over the past year.

In live mode, add &size=<YOUR_PIXEL_SIZE> to change the pixel size of the image for export (Right click to save). For example, &size=4000 will set the width of the image to be 4000 pixels.
